eaking it into words gives `[\"/\", \"Jesien\", \"/\", \"Zupy\"]`. It doesn't start with lowercase, doesn't have a mid-text sentence boundary, and the multi-word check shows no garbled words since the non-slash segments start with uppercase letters. The text uses `/` as separators, not `|`, and it's not a bullet or section label. With 4 words total, it passes all the hard filters.\n\nNow checking \"KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA\" — it's 26 characters and passes the basic checks. For the garbled test, the letters spell out a 23-letter sequence with 8 vowels, giving a ratio around 0.35, which is acceptable. It doesn't start with lowercase and has no other garbling indicators.\n\nMoving through the metadata filters: \"DLA 4 OSÓB\" matches the metadata pattern and correctly fails. \"PRZYGOTOWANIE 10 MIN\" and \"GOTOWANIE 30 MIN\" both fail because they contain the time duration pattern. Now examining \"UuIw\" — it's only 4 characters and doesn't match ingredient or number patterns, so I need to check if it's garbled. So `UuIw` is passing the hard filters even though it's clearly OCR garbage—the mixed-case pattern isn't being caught as garbled, and it has 4 letters so it avoids the single-word length check. Now I'm trying to understand why this nonsense string would rank higher than a legitimate multi-word phrase like `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA` in the embedding comparison.\n\nI'm looking at the bilingual title detection logic—it checks if the first position contains non-all-caps text, then filters for nearby all-caps entries to identify potential language pairs. Let me trace through what's happening with the scoring and position filtering... The layout-based detection extracts words longer than 2 characters from both the preceding text and the capitalized phrase, then checks for any overlap. Since there's no word match between them, the function returns true and incorrectly flags `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA` as a translation candidate when it's actually just a dish name.\